observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

1. Remit the unexpended balances to the respective Source Agencies in the total amount of ₱5,257.42;

2. Obtain MOA from the source agencies to establish the purpose of the FT and to ensure that FT is solely used for its intended purpose;
3. Request for write-off of the dormant balances that could no longer be accounted or settled amounting to ₱1,098,107.84 following the prescribed guidelines and procedures stated in COA Circular No. 2016-005;

4. Take-up the following proposed adjusting journal entry on the misclassified accounts in the total amount of ₱417,630.24 to present the correct balance of the affected accounts: and

	Due to NGAs	417,630.24		    Due to GOCCs	 417,630.24

5. Analyze the abnormal balance noted in the SL and ageing of payables amounting to ₱640,557.51 and make the necessary adjustments in the books once accounted.

We recommended that Management:

1. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to post the procurement opportunity in the PhilGEPS website, the website of the Procuring Entity concerned, and at any conspicuous place in the premises of the Procuring Entity for a period of at least three calendar days;

2. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to require the submission of the mandatory documents to be submitted by the suppliers and contractors before the award of contract;

3. Instruct the BAC to recommend the award of contracts to suppliers and contractors that are registered in the PhilGEPS;
4. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA, Contract and NTP, in the PhilGEPS website, the website of the Procuring Entity concerned, if available, and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the Procuring Entity within 10 days from issuance for contracts with ABC above ₱50,000.00;

5. Instruct the BAC to require the contractor to post the performance security for infrastructure projects procured through SVP; and

6. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that PR is prepared by the end-user or the authorized personnel, as the case may be.

We recommended that Management:

Provide its own engineered sanitary landfill so that it will not depend on other LGUs for disposal of its residual non-recyclable wastes;

Provide a fully equipped MRF to accommodate the volume of biodegradable and non-biodegradable wastes collected;

Ensure the establishment of MRF in every barangay or cluster barangays in compliance with the provisions of RA 9003;

Instruct the Solid Waste Management Officer to fast-track the revision of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan; and

Submit to the National Solid Waste Management Commission for approval in compliance with Section 16 of RA 9003.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the entry made on the receipt of PCSO Share by debiting the Due to GOCCs account and crediting the Due to Other Funds account under the Trust Fund books and by debiting the Due from Other Funds account and crediting the Prior Period Adjustment account in the General Fund books by the same amount of ₱186,708.92;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to transfer funds from the Trust Fund to the General Fund bank account in the amount of ₱186,708.92;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the receipt of share from the Lotto Charity Fund as income in the General Fund books using the account title “Share from PCSO”; and
Utilize the funds in the conduct of charity programs and activities consistent with the PCSO line-up of services under the Lotto Charity Fund.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the BAC and TWG to perform the post-qualification of bidders thoroughly by looking into the eligibility requirements like permits and licenses necessary in relation to the goods/services to be delivered/performed;
Instruct the TWG to conduct a site inspection of the bidder’s place of business and/or plant/factory before the award of the contract;
Impose sanctions on the concerned supplier and/or immediately issue a Blacklisting Order disqualifying the erring supplier from participating in the bidding of all government projects of the LGU; and
Forfeit the entire performance security for failure of the winning bidder to perform its obligations under the contract.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Property Officer in-charge to prepare the Property Inventory using the prescribed format and submit the same to the GSIS as the basis for the assessment of general insurance coverage of all insurable assets of the LGU; 
Instruct the Appraisal Committee to cause the appraisal of insurable properties of the LGU;
Provide sufficient amount in the Annual Budget to pay for the premiums of all insurable assets; and 
Secure the property insurance of non-insured government properties.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Require the HRMO Designate to prepare the payroll voucher or list of payees indicating their net payments for approval by the Local Chief Executive before the preparation of disbursement voucher for the cash advance for payroll;

b.	Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that amount of advances should be equal to the total net payments indicated in the approved payroll;

c.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that no additional cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made and to issue certification that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books; and

d.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the advances are properly obligated.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Provide its own engineered sanitary landfill so that it will not depend on other LGUs for disposal of its residual non-recyclable wastes;

b.	Provide a fully equipped MRF to accommodate the volume of biodegradable and non-biodegradable wastes collected;

c.	Ensure the establishment of MRF in every barangay or cluster barangays in compliance with the provisions of RA 9003;

d. Instruct the Solid Waste Management Officer to fast-track the revision of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan

e.  and submit to the National Solid Waste Management Commission for approval in compliance with Section 16 of RA 9003.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to submit immediately the unsubmitted financial transactions to the Audit Team for verification and evaluation to establish reliability, propriety and legality of the recorded transactions;
Direct the concerned department heads to revise the check and cash disbursement process in accordance with Sections 44 and 49 of MNGAS and ensure that all controls are in place;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to forward only the DVs to the Municipal Treasurer for preparation of check if all supporting documents relevant to the transactions are complete;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare check only upon obtaining certification from the Municipal Accountant on the completeness of the supporting documents;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to release all check payments to the payees in the Treasury Office and stop the practice of allowing the concerned department to do the job;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record only the check disbursement in the books upon issuance of check to the payee, and upon return by the Treasury Office of the DV duly acknowledged by the payee and its supporting documents, and record cash disbursements upon submission of liquidation report and its supporting documents;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer that all cash disbursements be paid in the Treasury Office and if payments cannot be made such as distribution of various financial assistance, ensure that these will be paid by an authorized disbursing officer of the Treasury Office; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit all recorded financial transactions and their supporting documents to the Audit Team within ten days of the ensuing month.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Assessor, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to cause the immediate retrieval of all necessary documents of ownership of the unregistered parcels of land and facilitate the transfer and registration with Land Registration Authority (LRA) in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the interest of the Municipality;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate funds to cover the expenses of transfer and registration of the parcels of land;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Assessor and Municipal Treasurer to prepare a master list of homeowners and to retrieve all pertinent documents evidencing sale; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Assessor and Municipal Treasurer to exert best efforts to establish the cost of the lot pertaining to the housing project of the Municipality and to calculate the cost of lot with title transferred to the homeowners to be derecognized from the books in order to present the correct balances of affected accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to facilitate the preparation of lapsing schedule to support depreciation expenses recorded and to be recorded in the future;
Require the Municipal Accountant to provide for the corresponding monthly depreciation costs for all the depreciable PPE accounts of the LGU to present correct balances of PPE accounts at any given period;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide complete description and cost segregation of road components for all road projects to the Municipal Accountant as basis for computation of depreciation expense for road networks; and
Restate the Statement of Financial Performance and Financial Position by making necessary correcting entries for the inclusion of prior years’ depreciation in the current year and for the noted misclassification of depreciation expense in the PPE accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record all procurement of supplies and materials as inventory following the Perpetual Inventory Method;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to monitor and control the inventory of supplies and materials through issuance of RIS and maintenance of stock cards for supplies;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to consolidate weekly the RIS issued and facilitate the preparation of SSMI which will be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the consumption and/or distribution to the appropriate expense accounts; and
Consider the creation of plantilla for General Services Officer who will take charge of controlling and monitoring the purchases and issuances of all supplies and materials of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Treasurer to maintain a local road inventory and road map and to periodically render RLRN, and furnish copies to the concerned offices;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to maintain Local Road Network Ledger Card and Local Road Network Property Card for each individual road networks, respectively; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to revise the disclosures in the road networks as presented in the NTFS in conformity with the guidelines.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Administrator in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to submit justification on the payment of scholarship assistance amounting to ₱5,500,000.00 even though the program is not supported with Sangguniang Bayan Ordinance and written policy or guidelines;
Require the Municipal Administrator to immediately submit the master list of scholars and their eligibilities to the Audit Team for evaluation;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit to the Audit Team the paid cash DVs and its supporting documents for audit; and
Require the Municipal Administrator with concurrence of the Sangguniang Bayan to develop well-defined guidelines and criteria on the screening, evaluation, selection, granting and monitoring of the qualified and deserving students of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit to the Audit Team the pertinent documents pertaining to meals, trainings conducted, and repairs and maintenance, as well as purchases made through SVP for audit to validate the payment thereof;
Fully account the items distributed to the intended beneficiaries and to submit the list of recipients with the corresponding quantity of the items received duly acknowledged by the intended beneficiaries, pictures on distribution and other pertinent documents to the Audit Team for evaluation;
Cause the immediate submission of certificate of acceptance or acknowledgment receipt of the authorized representatives of the different schools, pictures and other pertinent documents evidencing distribution or receipt by various schools; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to exercise prudence and diligence in his duties and responsibilities in the verification of the completeness of the documents for all transactions of the Municipality before payments are made.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:

Ensure the conduct of complete physical inventory of all municipal properties and the preparation and submission of the Report on the Physical Count of PPE, in prescribed format, to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to perform reconciliation of the actual physical count with the accounting records and to establish the cause/s of discrepancies and make appropriate adjustments as warranted;

Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively;



Direct the Municipal Treasurer to file and update Property Acknowledgement Receipt to properly identify the accountable officer in case of loss and maintain property tags on all properties of the Municipality; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to provide for the corresponding depreciation costs of the School Buildings, Slaughterhouses and Agricultural and Forestry Equipment.

We recommended that the Management:

Inform the Property Officer to periodically render Report of Local Road Networks, and furnish copies to the concerned offices.  Also, Municipal Engineer’s Office should provide the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;


Create an item for General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Network Inventory and Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for each individual road networks; and



Ensure coordination among LGU Offices to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:
Require the HRMO Designate to prepare the payroll voucher or list of payees indicating their net payments for approval by the Local Chief Executive before the preparation of disbursement voucher for the cash advance for payroll;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that amount of advances should be equal to the total net payments indicated in the approved payroll;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that no additional cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made and to issue certification that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the advances are properly obligated.
In a letter-reply, the Management commented that they will comply with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
Provide its own engineered sanitary landfill so that it will not depend on other LGUs for disposal of its residual non-recyclable wastes;
Provide a fully equipped MRF to accommodate the volume of biodegradable and non-biodegradable wastes collected;
Ensure the establishment of MRF in every barangay or cluster barangays in compliance with the provisions of RA 9003; and
Instruct the Solid Waste Management Officer to fast-track the revision of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan and submit to the National Solid Waste Management Commission for approval in compliance with Section 16 of RA 9003.
In a letter-reply, Management commented that will comply with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require all Accountable Officers to liquidate their cash advances on time; otherwise, impose administrative sanctions against them for any unjustifiable reasons due to failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period, in accordance with Section 89 of PD 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

Require the Municipal Accountant to provide certification that the previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books in compliance with the documentary requirements required under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and ensure that no additional cash advances be granted unless the previous cash advance was fully liquidated as required under the same COA Circular;

Ensure that claims beyond the allowable rates provided under Executive Order No. 77 dated March 15, 2019 are absolute necessary in the performance of the assignment by issuing a certification of the same; and


Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the amount granted for advances to officers and employees is the same as the amount shown in the duly approved Itinerary of Travel, respectively, and ensure that liquidations of cash advances are duly supported with documentary requirements as provided in COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspension.
